This simplifies to

Further simplification using the sine and cosine product sum formulas gives us

\[\frac{\sin 18^\circ (\cos 12^\circ + \cos 102^\circ)}{\sin 68^\circ  \cos 8^\circ - \cos 22^\circ \sin 98^\circ}.\]

\[\frac{\sin 18^\circ (2 \cos 57^\circ \cos 45^\circ)}{\sin 68^\circ  \cos 8^\circ - \cos 22^\circ \sin 98^\circ}.\]

Then, apply the cosine product sum formula to the numerator:

\[\frac{2 \sin 18^\circ \cos 57^\circ \cos 45^\circ}{\sin 68^\circ  \cos 8^\circ - \cos 22^\circ \sin 98^\circ}.\]

Given that 45 is \frac{\pi}{4}, this can be transformed in the following way: using the \cos \left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} identity: 

\[\frac{2 \sin 18^\circ \cos 57^\circ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}}{\sin 68^\circ  \cos 8^\circ - \cos 22^\circ \sin 98^\circ}.\]

This simplifies to 

\[\frac{\sin 18^\circ \cos 57^\circ \sqrt{2}}{\sin 68^\circ  \cos 8^\circ - \cos 22^\circ \sin 98^\circ}.\]
